The governments of Cook Islands, Federated States of Micronesia, Fiji, French Polynesia, Nauru, New Caledonia, Palau, Papua New Guinea, Republic of the Marshall Islands, Samoa, Solomon Islands, Tonga, Tuvalu, Vanuatu, and the United States of America held the first-ever U.S.-Pacific Islands Summit at the White House in Washington, D.C. They reaffirmed their commitment to working together to address the challenges of the climate crisis and geopolitical environment. They resolved to strengthen their partnership by enhancing diplomatic engagement, expanding development cooperation, and resolving unresolved issues related to the Compacts of Free Association. They also committed to bolstering Pacific regionalism, advancing progress on the Paris Agreement, and supporting each other to prepare and respond to natural disasters. Furthermore, they pledged to protect the Pacific Ocean and enhance maritime security, strengthen cooperation on health-related issues, expand opportunities for all peoples, and address the legacies of conflict and promote nuclear nonproliferation. They outlined a way forward for the partnership, emphasizing mutual respect, transparency, and accountability.